One of the most significant events that occurred in Guinea in the past 20 years is the 2008 military coup. On December 23, 2008, the then-President Lansana Conté, who had been in power for 24 years, passed away. This led to a power struggle within the military, and a group of junior military officers under Captain Moussa Dadis Camara seized control of the government.

The military junta, known as the National Council for Democracy and Development (CNDD), led Guinea for the next year, during which the country experienced widespread human rights abuses, political repression, and economic decline. In September 2009, the most significant event related to this period occurred when security forces opened fire on a peaceful protest against potential military rule, leading to the killing of more than 150 civilians and the raping of many women. This event, known as the 2009 Guinea massacre, shocked the international community and further deteriorated Guinea's political situation.

However, this event also marked a turning point in Guinea's history. Following international condemnation, negotiations were initiated that ultimately led to the establishment of a transitional government, including civil society representatives and the military, which aimed to restore civilian rule. These negotiations resulted in the election of Alpha Condé as president in 2010, marking the country's first democratic transfer of power.
